,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,66,16),(425,'Incorrect','Imagine that you have 6 pens with lids. If you take the lid off each pen (i.e., \"dissociate\" the pen), do you have 6 pen bodies and 6 pen lids? \n\nIf you start with 6 HCl molecules, do you get 6 hydronium and 6 chloride ions?\n\nYour equation does not yield the result you would expect given the above.',0,0,1,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,54,17),(426,'Charge Balance Equation','The charge balance equation (there is only one) keeps track of the total charge of the solution, which must be neutral. The concentration of positive charge must therefore match the concentration of negative charge.\n\nChoose the correct charge balance (M.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq).',0,0,0,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,61,18),(427,'pH of 0.010 M HCl Completed','The set of systematic equations is shown for HCl (aq). One can immediately arrive at the answer of [H3O+] = 0.010 M, which corresponds to pH 2.\n\nAgain, the systematic approach is not strictly needed for a solution of strong acid. Nonetheless, it mirrors the intuitive process of solving the problem.',0,0,0,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,67,19),(428,'Incorrect','To write a C.B. equation, sum the positive charge and negative charge on opposite sides of the equation. Each ion contributes a total charge equal to its concentration multiplied by the charge per ion.\n\nThe C.B. equation does not include the initial concentrations of acids and bases.',0,0,1,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,54,20),(429,'What is acetic acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,68,21),(430,'Weak Acids','What is the principle characteristic of weak acids?',0,0,0,0,'2015-11-18 00:57:37','2015-11-18 00:57:37',21,61,22),(431,'Acetic Acid is a Weak Acid','We will now calculate the pH of a 0.10 M aqueous solution of acetic acid using the systematic equations approach.',0,0,0,0,'2015-11-18 00:5