arges in the entire solution. This equation must therefore include ions from both the dissociation of acetic acid and from the dissociation of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,53),(568,'Incorrect','There is only one concentration of hydronium in a solution regardless of the acid source. There is no need to count its concentration twice just because there are two acids in solution.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,54),(569,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The charge balance equation for the mixture must include both the chloride and acetate counter-ions, plus the usual hydronium and hydroxide.\n\nAre the two mass balance equations for the mixture any different than the mass balance equations for hydrochloric acid and acetic acid separately?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,86,55),(570,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The equilibrium expression for the dissociation of acetic acid is unchanged.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,85,56),(571,'Incorrect','Hydronium notwithstanding, the hydrochloric acid and acetic acid to produce the same ions in solution. The mass balance equations are therefore unchanged.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,57),(572,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. We now have a complete set of equations for the mixture of 0.10 M acetic acid and 0.010 M hydrochloric acid.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,87,58),(573,'Sytematic Equations: Assumptions','What assumptions can make to simplify the solution to this system of equations?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,87,59),(574,'A Potentially Good Assumption','If you assume that [CH3COO-] << [Cl-], then you have assumed that the acetic acid does not contribute to the pH of the solution of 0.010 M hydrochloric acid and 0.10 M acetic acid.\n\nThis may or may not be the case. For the moment, let\'s assume its not a valid assumption and continue.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,66,60),(575,'Simplified System of Equations','With the assumptions that [OH-] and the dissociation of acetic acid are negligible, the equations simplify as shown above. \n\nThe equations can be algebraically reduced to a quadratic equation in terms of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,89,61),(576,'Solving the Simplified Equation','The calculated pH is 1.99. \n\nIf we had assumed the acetic acid had no effect on the pH with hydrochloric acid present, the calculated pH would have been 2.00. Thus, such as assumption would have been acceptable.\n\nWhen would this assumption become less likely to be valid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,90,62),(577,'Incorrect','Both the concentration of hydrochloric acid relative to the acetic acid and the strength of the weak acid will affect the contribution of the weak acid to the overall solution pH.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,63),(578,'Correct. Both the concentration of strong acid and strength of the weak acid are important.','With 0.0010 M HCl (aq) and 0.10 M CH3OOH (aq), the pH would 2.71 (vs. 3.00 for HCl alone). \n\nWith Ka = 1.8E-3 for 0.10 M weak acid (vs. 1.8E-5 for acetic acid) the pH with 0.010 M HCl (aq) would be 1.71 (vs. 1.99 in the current acetic acid mixture).',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,66,64),(579,'Success!','Congratulations! You have complete this scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,55,65),(580,'Incorrect','If 0.10 M acetic acid had minimal effect on the pH when mixed with 0.010 M hydrochloric acid, then a weak acid with a smaller dissociation constant will have even less effect (i.e., virtually none).',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 01:57:12','2016-01-08 01:57:12',24,54,66),(581,'Scenario','We will work through the above problem conceptually and, to some extent, mathematically.',1,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,56,1),(582,'Scenario',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,57,2),(583,'What is hydrochloric acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,59,3),(584,'Strong Acids','What is the principle characteristic of strong acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,61,4),(585,'Incorrect','There are only a few strong acids in water. You should be able to recognize these acids.\n\nStrong acids include hydrochloric acid, hydrobromic acid, hydroiodic acid, chloric acid, perchloric acid, nitric acid, and sulfuric acid (first ionization only).',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,60,5),(586,'Incorrect','STRONG acids are characterized by COMPLETE dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.\n\nWEAK acids are characterized by PARTIAL dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,6),(587,'Incorrect','Acids are characterized by their dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counterion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,7),(588,'Concentration of Hydronium','Given that HCl completely dissociates in water to form hydronium and chloride, what will be the concentration of hydronium in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,62,8),(589,'Concentration of Chloride','What will be the concentration of chloride in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,63,9),(590,'Incorrect','The concentration of hydronium and chloride are related to the initial concentration of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,10),(591,'pH of 0.010 M Hydrochloric Acid','The pH of 0.010 M HCl (aq) is calculated as shown, yielding a result of pH 2.\n\nThis result can be also be obtained from a systematic equations approach. Although unnecessary for strong acids, an systematic equations approach will prove useful later, so we’ll apply it to HCl (aq) first.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,77,11),(592,'Systematic Equations Approach','The systematic approach has three bases: (1) equilibrium constant equation(s); (2) mass balance equation(s); and (3) a charge balance equation.\n\nCan an equilibrium constant equation be written for HCl (aq) or any other strong acid in water?',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,61,12),(593,'Incorrect','Strong acids completely dissociate and do not have an equilibrium constant associated with that dissociation (i.e., Ka is not defined because the equilibrium lies too far in favour of the product ions). \n\nTherefore, an equilibrium constant equation cannot be written.',0,0,1,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,54,13),(594,'Mass Balance Equation','Mass balance equations keep track of the conservation of matter. No matter how an acid or base dissociates, the amounts of the conjugate species must add up to the amount originally added.\n\nComplete the mass balance (M.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq) by filling in the blank.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,65,14),(595,'Yes, but...','You\'re not wrong; however, you only know the concentration of hydronium because of your intuitive knowledge of strong acid behaviour.\n\nIf a weak acid were considered, or if there was another acidic or basic species in solution, you would not immediately know the concentration of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,66,15),(596,'Think Counter-Ion','The chloride counter-ion is neither an acid nor a base. We can therefore always know its concentration from the amount of HCl (or other chloride-containing salts) added to solution.',0,0,0,0,'2016-01-08 19:04:41','2016-01-08 19:04:41',25,66,16),(597,'Incorrect','Imagine that you have 6 pens with lids. If you take the lid off each pen (i.e., \"dissociate\" t