s','That\'s not quite right.',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-22 23:52:40','2016-02-22 23:53:10',31,NULL,24),(920,'Oops','That\'s not quite right',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-23 00:10:31','2016-02-23 00:10:40',31,NULL,25),(921,'Oops','That\'s not quite right...',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-23 00:14:27','2016-02-23 00:15:21',31,NULL,26),(922,'Equilibrium','The following scenario is based on question 4 from this year\'s CHEM 211 test 1. \n\nThis scenario is designed to help you work through each part of the question, and provide feedback on incorrect answers.',1,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 08:14:49','2016-03-09 23:46:57',33,NULL,1),(923,'Question 4a-i','Which of the following is the mass balance equation for the solubility of AgBr (K_sp = 5.0x10^-13) in a solution of 0.30 M NaBr(aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 20:03:04','2016-03-10 19:41:53',33,NULL,2),(924,'Choice A','Incorrect. AgBr (s) is a solid and therefore does not have a concentration.',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 20:22:54','2016-03-10 19:41:12',33,NULL,3),(925,'Choice B','Incorrect. NaBr is a soluble salt that will fully dissociate in water to yield Na+ and Br- ions.',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 20:24:42','2016-03-10 19:41:35',33,NULL,4),(927,'Choice C','Correct. What is the correct assumption?',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 20:26:06','2016-03-10 19:42:58',33,NULL,5),(928,'Choice D','Almost.... [Br-] will come from dissociation of both AgBr (s) and NaBr (s), but you know that NaBr will dissociate fully (almost all sodium salts do). Therefore, [Na+] = 0.30 M, and the best equation is 0.30 M + [Ag+] = [Br-].',0,0,0,0,'2016-02-29 20:35:01','2016-03-10 19:42:24',33,NULL,6),(929,'Choice A','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-01 08:27:19','2016-03-01 08:38:09',33,NULL,7),(931,'Choice B','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-01 08:27:48','2016-03-01 08:28:16',33,NULL,8),(932,'Question 4a-ii','Which of the following is the correct mass balance equation for 1 µM of an acidic indicator dye, HIn, with pKa = 9.0, in aqueous solution buffered at pH 8.5 ?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-01 08:28:28','2016-03-10 19:44:09',33,NULL,9)