-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,4),(1250,'Choice C','Correct. What is the correct assumption?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,5),(1251,'Choice D','Almost.... [Br-] will come from dissociation of both AgBr (s) and NaBr (s), but you know that NaBr will dissociate fully (almost all sodium salts do). Therefore, [Na+] = 0.30 M, and the best equation is 0.30 M + [Ag+] = [Br-].',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,6),(1252,'Choice A','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,7),(1253,'Choice B','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,8),(1254,'Question 4a-ii','Which of the following is the correct mass balance equation for 1 µM of an acidic indicator dye, HIn, with pKa = 9.0, in aqueous solution buffered at pH 8.5 ?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,9),(1255,'Choice C','Incorrect.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,116,10),(1256,'Choice A','Incorrect. For aqueous solutions, [H3O+], [H2O] and [OH-] never show up in mass balance equations. There is so much excess water that we don\'t need to keep track of it.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,11),(1257,'Choice B','Incorrect.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,115,12),(1258,'Choice C','Correct. \n\nFor the same 1 µM solution of an acidic indicator dye, HIn (pKa = 9.0), buffered at pH 8.5:\n\nWhat assumptions can be made?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,13),(1259,'Choice D','Incorrect. A mass balance equation must include HIn and In-. This equation is a charge balance equation, which, aside from not being a mass balance equation, does not apply in an unspecified buffer.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,14),(1260,'Choice A','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,15),(1261,'Choice B','Incorrect. [HIn] will be larger than [In-] because pH < pKa; however, the pH is within +/- 1 of the pKa, so there will be a significant amount of both HIn and In-.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,16),(1262,'Choice C','Incorrect. [HIn] will be larger than [In-] because pH < pKa; however, the pH is within +/- 1 of the pKa, so there will be a significant amount of both HIn and In-.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,17),(1263,'Choice D','Incorrect. If you had a concentrated, unbuffered solution of indicator, then this would apply. But this does not apply to very dilute indicator in buffer because the indicator responds to the buffer pH.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,18),(1264,'Question 4a-iii','The mass balance equation for 0.010 M Na2CO3 (aq) is: \n0.010 M = [H2CO3] + [HCO3-] + [CO32-] \n\nWhat assumption(s) can be made?\n\nNote that for H2CO3: K_a1 = 4.5 x 10^-7 and K_a2 = 4.7 x 10^-11',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,19),(1265,'Choice A','Incorrect. Na2CO3 dissolves to give 0.010 M CO32-. You will start with this amount and only some will dissociate because you have a weak base. [CO32-] will not be negligible. Think about K_b!',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,20),(1266,'Choice D','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,21),(1267,'Choice C','Incorrect. Na2CO3 dissolves to give 0.010 M CO32-. You will start with this amount and only some will dissociate because you have a weak base. [CO32-] will not be negligible. Think about K_b!',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,22),(1268,'Choice B','Incorrect. Imagine the ionization process starting from CO32- and then work backwards looking at K values.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,23),(1269,'Choice E','Incorrect.  The value of K_b1 is not much smaller than the initial concentration. CO32- is a weak but still good base, thus [HCO3-] will not be negligible.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,24),(1270,'Question 4a-v','Which of the following is the charge balance equation for a solution of 1.0 M NH4Cl (aq) and 0.20 M NaCl (aq) ?\n\nNote that the ammonium ion has pKa = 9.24.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,25),(1271,'Choice A','Almost. The equation you selected assumes no acid-base behaviour. NH4+ is a weak acid.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,26),(1272,'Choice B','Correct. What is the assumption?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,27),(1273,'Choice A','Incorrect. NH3 is a weak base, but NH4+ is a weak acid. The solution will be acidic.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,28),(1274,'Choice B','Correct!  \n\nYou have now completed the scenario.  Your progress has been saved and you may return to the main menu.',0,1,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,29),(1275,'Choice C','Incorrect. Are you dissolving an acid or a base?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,30),(1276,'Choice D','Incorrect.The [Na+] is 20% of the initial concentration of NH4Cl (aq).',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,31),(1277,'Choice C','Incorrect. All ions, including spectator ions like sodium, must be included in the charge balance equation.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,32),(1278,'Choice D','Incorrect. The equation you selected is a mass balance equation.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,33),(1279,'Choice E','Incorrect. All ions, including spectator ions like sodium, must be included in the charge balance equation.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,NULL,34),(1280,'Choice D','Incorrect.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-12 18:58:58','2016-03-12 18:58:58',43,116,35),(1281,'Introduction','This scenario will ask you to work through a set of question that originally appeared on the CHEM 211 2015 