,(1398,'Advantages of photodiode array instruments','Correct!\n\nNow consider the opposite: Which of the following is an advantage of a spectrophotometer with a single-beam photodiode array (PDA) detector compared to a double-beam spectrophotometer with two PMT detectors?',0,0,0,1,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,22),(1399,'Correct!','Photodiode array detectors collect the entire range of wavelengths dispersed by the grating, with each diode acting as its own exit slit. \n\nAs a result, instruments with a PDA detector:\n(1) allow faster measurements (the whole spectrum can be measured at once)\nAND\n(2) do not require a moving grating',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,23),(1400,'Ooops','That\'s not quite right.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,24),(1401,'Oops','That\'s not quite right',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,25),(1402,'Oops','That\'s not quite right...',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,26),(1403,'That\'s not quite right...','As stated in the problem, the double-beam instrument uses two different PMT detectors, which will each experience their own noise.  It\'s therefore not possible to correct for detector variations with this setup.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,27),(1404,'That\'s not quite right...','Remember that the double-beam instrument uses a grating monochromator with an entrance slit and an exit slit.  The detected wavelength is selected by adjusting the angle of the grating, so that the desired wavelength passes through the exit slit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,28),(1405,'Incorrect.','PDA instruments are usually single-beam instruments, and thus are unable to correct for noise.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,29),(1406,'You\'re done!','Congratulations!  You have completed this scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:34:22','2016-03-16 02:34:22',46,NULL,30),(1407,'Equilibrium','The following scenario is based on question 4 from this year\'s CHEM 211 test 1. \n\nThis scenario is designed to help you work through each part of the question, and provide feedback on incorrect answers.',1,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,1),(1408,'Question 4a-i','Which of the following is the mass balance equation for the solubility of AgBr (K_sp = 5.0x10^-13) in a solution of 0.30 M NaBr(aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,2),(1409,'Choice A','Incorrect. AgBr (s) is a solid and therefore does not have a concentration.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,3),(1410,'Choice B','Incorrect. NaBr is a soluble salt that will fully dissociate in water to yield Na+ and Br- ions.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,4),(1411,'Choice C','Correct. What is the correct assumption?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,5),(1412,'Choice D','Almost.... [Br-] will come from dissociation of both AgBr (s) and NaBr (s), but you know that NaBr will dissociate fully (almost all sodium salts do). Therefore, [Na+] = 0.30 M, and the best equation is 0.30 M + [Ag+] = [Br-].',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,6),(1413,'Choice A','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,7),(1414,'Choice B','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,8),(1415,'Question 4a-ii','Which of the following is the correct mass balance equation for 1 µM of an acidic indicator dye, HIn, with pKa = 9.0, in aqueous solution buffered at pH 8.5 ?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,9),(1416,'Choice C','Incorrect.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,116,10),(1417,'Choice A','Incorrect. For aqueous solutions, [H3O+], [H2O] and [OH-] never show up in mass balance equations. There is so much excess water that we don\'t need to keep track of it.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,11),(1418,'Choice B','Incorrect.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,115,12),(1419,'Choice C','Correct. \n\nFor the same 1 µM solution of an acidic indicator dye, HIn (pKa = 9.0), buffered at pH 8.5:\n\nWhat assumptions can be made?',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,13),(1420,'Choice D','Incorrect. A mass balance equation must include HIn and In-. This equation is a charge balance equation, which, aside from not being a mass balance equation, does not apply in an unspecified buffer.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,14),(1421,'Choice A','Correct.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,15),(1422,'Choice B','Incorrect. [HIn] will be larger than [In-] because pH < pKa; however, the pH is within +/- 1 of the pKa, so there will be a significant amount of both HIn and In-.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,16),(1423,'Choice C','Incorrect. [HIn] will be larger than [In-] because pH < pKa; however, the pH is within +/- 1 of the pKa, so there will be a significant amount of both HIn and In-.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,17),(1424,'Choice D','Incorrect. If you had a concentrated, unbuffered solution of indicator, then this would apply. But this does not apply to very dilute indicator in buffer because the indicator responds to the buffer pH.',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,18),(1425,'Question 4a-iii','The mass balance equation for 0.010 M Na2CO3 (aq) is: \n0.010 M = [H2CO3] + [HCO3-] + [CO32-] \n\nWhat assumption(s) can be made?\n\nNote that for H2CO3: K_a1 = 4.5 x 10^-7 and K_a2 = 4.7 x 10^-11',0,0,0,0,'2016-03-16 02:35:05','2016-03-16 02:35:05',47,NULL,19),(1426,'Choice A','Incorrect. Na2CO3 dissolves to give 0.010 M CO32-. You will start with this amount and only some will dissociate because you have a weak base. [CO32-