2',52,NULL,27),(1619,'Incorrect','Sorry, that\'s not quite right.  Consider the wavelength range produced by each type of light source.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,28),(1620,'Molar absorptivity of oxy-hemoglobin','In fact, hemoglobin absorbs over a wide range of visible and IR wavelengths, as shown by the figure above.  What wavelength should be used in order to maximize the sensitivity of the absorbance measurement?',0,0,0,1,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,120,29),(1621,'Oops...','That\'s not quite right.  Consider the relationship between the molar absorptivity  (plotted on the y axis) and absorbance.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,120,30),(1622,'Correct','Now that you have a working instrument, you need to prepare 5 standard solutions to perform an external standards calibration. Knowing that your samples will contain ~10-15 g/dL hemoglobin, which set of standard concentrations should you use for calibration?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,31),(1623,'Hemoglobin calibration','You measure 5 standard solutions with hemoglobin concentrations ranging from 0-30 g/dL and plot them to get the calibration curve shown above.  What should you do next?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,121,32),(1624,'Incorrect','That\'s not quite right.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,33),(1625,'Correct','At the upper end of the expected hemoglobin concentration (15-20 g/dL) the Absorbance is > 1, resulting in unreliable measurements.  (Notice that the 30 g/dL sample gives the same absorbance as ~12 g/dL)  Diluting the standards AND samples is required to achieve a reliable calibration.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,122,34),(1626,'Hemoglobin complete!','Congratulations. You have successfully developed a method to analyze the concentration of hemoglobin using absorbance with an appropriate light source, wavelength, and calibration standards!  You can now return and choose another analyte for method development.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,35),(1627,'Goodbye!','You have left the scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,36),(1628,'Incorrect','At the upper end of the expected hemoglobin concentration (15-20 g/dL) the Absorbance is > 1 and non-linear (Notice that the 30 g/dL sample gives the same absorbance as ~12 g/dL).  Measuring standards OR samples in this concentration range will result in unreliable measured values.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,121,37),(1629,'Spectrophotometer components','Correct.  Having chosen a tungsten lamp and an optimal wavelength (410 nm), you need to assemble your spectrophotometer.  Choose an option that lists the required components in a correct and working order.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,38),(1630,'Oops...','That\'s not quite right.  Think carefully about the purpose of each component when building your instrument.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-03 20:11:22','2016-05-03 20:11:22',52,NULL,39),(1631,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','Iron is the second most abundant metal in the Earth’s crust, the main component of many structural materials (e.g., various types of steel), and an important dietary element with important biochemical roles.',1,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,18,1),(1632,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of iron in a sample can be determined spectrophotometrically. Phenanthroline is a ligand that can coordinate to iron(II) as shown above. The iron(ii) phenanthroline complex has an orange colour, whereas the iron(II) and phenanthroline alone have no colour.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,19,2),(1633,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of iron originally present in a solution is proportional to the amount of the orange complex formed. The amount of complex formed can be measured from the amount of green light that is absorbed by the solution. The details of this type of measurement are explained in another unit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,19,3),(1634,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','For this exercise, it is sufficient to know that the solution containing iron and phenanthroline is aliquoted into a transparent sample cell, light with a wavelength of 554 nm passes through the sample cell, and the amount of light lost traversing the cell is measured.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,22,4),(1635,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of light lost traversing the sample is used to calculate its “absorbance.”  To ensure that the light lost is attributable to the absorption of photons by the iron(II) phenanthroline complex, the absorbance of the sample cell containing only solvent is measured as a negative control.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,23,5),(1636,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The difference between the absorbance, A, measured for the sample and the blank is linearly proportional to the concentration, c, of the iron(II) phenanthroline complex, although deviations from linearity can sometimes be observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,24,6),(1637,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','This is an example of a calibration curve that plots absorbance, A, versus the concentration, c, of an analyte. The slope, k, of the line of best fit through the data points can be used in combination with the equation A = kc to determine the concentration of iron in an unknown solution.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,26,7),(1638,'Scenario','You will statistically analyze calibration data for the analysis of iron using phenanthroline and spectrophotometry. The calibration data will be used to determine the concentration of iron(II) in an unknown sample, and your results will be compared to the results from another analysis.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,28,8),(1639,'Raw Data','The table shows the raw data measured for the blank and four replicates each of six standard solutions with different concentrations of iron(II) in the presence of excess phenanthroline. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,37,9),(1640,'Blank Corrected Data','The table now shows the data for the four replicates of each standard solution with the average value of the blank samples subtracted. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,38,10),(1641,'Do Not Ignore Blank Samples!','Blank samples, a type of negative control, are very important. Measurement of blank samples allows data to be corrected for contributions to a measured signal that do not arise from the analyte.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,54,11),(1642,'F-test?','An F-test is used to compare the precision between two measurements. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,NULL,12),(1643,'G-test?','A G-test is used identify outliers, assuming a normally distributed data set. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,NULL,13),(1644,'t-test?','A t-test is typically used to determine if two data sets are significantly different from one another. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,NULL,14),(1645,'Plot of the Data','The graph shows the data for each replicate of the standard solutions. \n\nAre you satisfied with this plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,36,15),(1646,'Averages and Standard Deviations','The table now shows the average absorbance values and their standard deviations for the six standard solutions.\n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,39,16),(1647,'Calibration Plot','The graph shows the average measured absorbance versus the concentration of iron(II). The error bars represent one standard deviation. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,35,17),(1648,'Be Critical of the Data!','Fitting the data with a line would often be logical at this point. However, the error bars are significantly larger for two of the standard solutions than for the others. \n\nYou would be well-advised to re-examine the data table--the larger errors do not appear to be due to greater random error.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,54,18),(1649,'Consider a Different Option','The t-test is not useful at this point in the data analysis because there is no second data set to which to compare the current data set.\n\nSimilarly, the F-test is not useful without a second data for comparison.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,54,19),(1650,'G-Test Results','For each standard concentration, the table shows the calculated G-value for the data point furthest from the mean of all of the replicate values. The critical G-value is 1.463 (at 95% confidence).\n\nWhat data points can be rejected from the data set as outliers?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:42','2016-05-31 01:18:42',53,40,20),(1651,'Incorrect','If the calculated G-value for a data point is larger than the critical G-value for the desired confidence level, then that point can be rejected as an outlier.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,21),(1652,'Mind Your Data!','When possible, replicate data points are plotted on graphs as an average value with error bars representing the standard deviation.\n\nIn addition, do one or more points appear to be anomalous?',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,22),(1653,'Revised Data Set','The revised data set, with outliers removed, is shown. The averages and standard deviations have been recalculated.\n\nNow how do you want to proceed with the analysis?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,41,23),(1654,'Calibration Plot (Outliers Removed)','The graph shows the average measured absorbance versus the concentration of iron(II). The error bars represent one standard deviation. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,42,24),(1655,'Fitted Calibration Plot','The entire range of data has been fitted with a line using least-squares regression. \n\nAre you satisfied with this plot?\n\nRecall: A plot of absorbance versus concentration is expected to be linear, with the general form A = kc, although deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,43,25),(1656,'Recall: Backgound Information','A plot of absorbance versus concentration is expected to be linear, with the general form A = kc, although deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,42,26),(1657,'Partial Linear Fit to Calibration Plot','What range of standard solutions do you want to fit with a line?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,42,27),(1658,'Good Thinking but not the Best Choice','There are many instances in which non-linear fits are warranted, and other instances where a purely empirical fit to data is useful. In this case, however, a linear trend is expected from first principles and is best to work within these constraints.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,28),(1659,'Not a Good Fit','The data point for the standard solution with the highest concentration clearly deviates from the linear trend. It was also noted that deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1. This point should be excluded from the linear fit.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,29),(1660,'Two Points Do Not Make a Line','At least three points are needed to fit a straight line (and preferably more in practice).',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,30),(1661,'Calibration Result','A line through all of the data points except the highest concentration of standard solution is shown with its equation of fit.\n\nAlso shown are the absorbance values and calculated concentrations for four replicate measurements of an unknown iron(II)-containing solution.\n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,48,31),(1662,'Not a Bad Choice, Not the Best Choice','Although three or four data points could define a straight line, it is clear from extrapolating the corresponding linear fits that all the data up to and including the fifth point fall on a line.\n\nIn general, it is best to fit as many points as possible without reducing the quality of the fit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,44,32),(1663,'Save Yourself Some Work','While statistical tests are important tools for making decision, your critical thinking skills remain essential.\n\nFrom inspection, there is clearly no outlier in this data set.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,33),(1664,'Uknown Sample Results','The summary of results for your analysis of the unknown sample is shown.\n\nHow will you report your overall result with 95% confidence?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,49,34),(1665,'Incorrect','Neither the G-statistic nor the F-statistic will help you report a confidence interval.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,35),(1666,'t-Test Result','The calculated value of t was less than the critical value at the 95% confidence level. \n\nWhat do you conclude?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,52,36),(1667,'Additional Comparison','How will you determine if there is a significant difference in average result between the two analyses?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,51,37),(1668,'Review Hypothesis Testing','Many statistical tests evaluate the null hypothesis by comparing a calculated value to a critical value. If the calculated value is larger than the critical value, then the null hypothesis is rejected and there is a statistically significant difference between the two things being compared.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,38),(1669,'Incorrect','Neither a G-test nor a t-test will determine if the two analyses have statistically different precision.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,39),(1670,'F-test Result','The calculated value of F was smaller than the critical value at the 95% confidence level.\n\nWhat do you conclude?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,53,40),(1671,'Congratulations!','You have analyzed calibration data, used that data to determine the concentration of iron(II) in an unknown sample, and obtained results that agree with those obtained by your colleague.',0,1,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,55,41),(1672,'Confidence Interval','With application of the t-statistic, you obtain the result shown, at the 95% confidence level.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,50,42),(1673,'Sample versus Population Stats','Reporting plus/minus two standard deviations would be correct if you had measured more than 20 replicates. In this case, population statistics would have applied. \n\nHere, much fewer replicates were measured, and thus sample statistics apply.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,43),(1674,'Comparison to Another Analysis','A comparison between your results and the results obtained by a colleague for the same unknown sample are shown.\n\nHow will you determine if there is a difference in precision between the two analyses?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,51,44),(1675,'Incorrect','Neither a F-test nor a G-test will help you determine if the average results of the two analyses are different.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:18:43','2016-05-31 01:18:43',53,54,45),(1676,'Scenario','We will work through the above problem conceptually and, to some extent, mathematically.',1,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,56,1),(1677,'Scenario',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,57,2),(1678,'What is hydrochloric acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,59,3),(1679,'Strong Acids','What is the principle characteristic of strong acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,61,4),(1680,'Incorrect','There are only a few strong acids in water. You should be able to recognize these acids.\n\nStrong acids include hydrochloric acid, hydrobromic acid, hydroiodic acid, chloric acid, perchloric acid, nitric acid, and sulfuric acid (first ionization only).',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,60,5),(1681,'Incorrect','STRONG acids are characterized by COMPLETE dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.\n\nWEAK acids are characterized by PARTIAL dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counter-ion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,6),(1682,'Incorrect','Acids are characterized by their dissociation in water to form hydronium and a counterion.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,7),(1683,'Concentration of Hydronium','Given that HCl completely dissociates in water to form hydronium and chloride, what will be the concentration of hydronium in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,62,8),(1684,'Concentration of Chloride','What will be the concentration of chloride in 0.010 M HCl (aq)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,63,9),(1685,'Incorrect','The concentration of hydronium and chloride are related to the initial concentration of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,10),(1686,'pH of 0.010 M Hydrochloric Acid','The pH of 0.010 M HCl (aq) is calculated as shown, yielding a result of pH 2.\n\nThis result can be also be obtained from a systematic equations approach. Although unnecessary for strong acids, an systematic equations approach will prove useful later, so we’ll apply it to HCl (aq) first.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,77,11),(1687,'Systematic Equations Approach','The systematic approach has three bases: (1) equilibrium constant equation(s); (2) mass balance equation(s); and (3) a charge balance equation.\n\nCan an equilibrium constant equation be written for HCl (aq) or any other strong acid in water?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,61,12),(1688,'Incorrect','Strong acids completely dissociate and do not have an equilibrium constant associated with that dissociation (i.e., Ka is not defined because the equilibrium lies too far in favour of the product ions). \n\nTherefore, an equilibrium constant equation cannot be written.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,13),(1689,'Mass Balance Equation','Mass balance equations keep track of the conservation of matter. No matter how an acid or base dissociates, the amounts of the conjugate species must add up to the amount originally added.\n\nComplete the mass balance (M.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq) by filling in the blank.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,65,14),(1690,'Yes, but...','You\'re not wrong; however, you only know the concentration of hydronium because of your intuitive knowledge of strong acid behaviour.\n\nIf a weak acid were considered, or if there was another acidic or basic species in solution, you would not immediately know the concentration of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,66,15),(1691,'Think Counter-Ion','The chloride counter-ion is neither an acid nor a base. We can therefore always know its concentration from the amount of HCl (or other chloride-containing salts) added to solution.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,66,16),(1692,'Incorrect','Imagine that you have 6 pens with lids. If you take the lid off each pen (i.e., \"dissociate\" the pen), do you have 6 pen bodies and 6 pen lids? \n\nIf you start with 6 HCl molecules, do you get 6 hydronium and 6 chloride ions?\n\nYour equation does not yield the result you would expect given the above.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,17),(1693,'Charge Balance Equation','The charge balance equation (there is only one) keeps track of the total charge of the solution, which must be neutral. The concentration of positive charge must therefore match the concentration of negative charge.\n\nChoose the correct charge balance (C.B.) equation for 0.010 M HCl (aq).',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,61,18),(1694,'pH of 0.010 M HCl Completed','The set of systematic equations is shown for HCl (aq). One can immediately arrive at the answer of [H3O+] = 0.010 M, which corresponds to pH 2.\n\nAgain, the systematic approach is not strictly needed for a solution of strong acid. Nonetheless, it mirrors the intuitive process of solving the problem.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,67,19),(1695,'Incorrect','To write a C.B. equation, sum the positive charge and negative charge on opposite sides of the equation. Each ion contributes a total charge equal to its concentration multiplied by the charge per ion.\n\nThe C.B. equation does not include the initial concentrations of acids and bases.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,20),(1696,'What is acetic acid?',NULL,0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,68,21),(1697,'Weak Acids','What is the principle characteristic of weak acids?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,61,22),(1698,'Acetic Acid is a Weak Acid','We will now calculate the pH of a 0.10 M aqueous solution of acetic acid using the systematic equations approach.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,69,23),(1699,'Equilibrium Constant Equation','Which of the above is the correct equilibrium equation corresponding to the acid dissociation constant, Ka.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,70,24),(1700,'Incorrect','The equilibrium constant equation is products over reactants.\n\nWhen water is the solvent, it does not enter in the equilibrium constant equation because its concentration is very large and thus effectively constant.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,25),(1701,'Mass Balance Equation','What terms complete the right hand side of the mass balance equation for 0.10 M acetic acid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,71,26),(1702,'Incorrect','A mass balance equation of 0.10 M = [CH3COO–] would only be true if acetic acid were a strong acid.\n\nAcetic acid is a weak acid, so a significant amount of undissociated CH3COOH will remain.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,27),(1703,'Incorrect','Hydronium is derived from water, which is in huge excess relative to any added acid or base. Mass balance equations with hydronium and, similarly, hydroxide, cannot usually be written.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,28),(1704,'Incorrect','Hydronium is derived from water, which is in huge excess relative to any added acid or base. Mass balance equations with hydronium and, similarly, hydroxide, cannot usually be written.\n\nIn addition, acetic acid is a weak acid, so a significant amount of undissociated CH3COOH will remain.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,29),(1705,'Charge Balance Equation','Choose the correct charge balance equation.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,72,30),(1706,'System of Equations for Acetic Acid','These equations comprise a complete system for determining the concentration of hydronium (or any other species) in a 0.10 M aqueous solution of acetic acid.\n\nNote that the equation for the autoionization water was added. This equation is always applicable in water.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,74,31),(1707,'Incorrect','The charge balance equation should contain no uncharged species, and total negative charge must equal the total positive charge.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,NULL,32),(1708,'Systematic Equations: Algebra','The M.B. equation can be substituted into the Ka equation to yield an expression for acetate in terms of hydronium. This new equation can be substituted into the C.B. equation along with the Kw equation. The result is a quadratic equation for hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,74,33),(1709,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','The mathematics can be simplified by making assumptions based on  knowledge of the chemistry of the system.\n\nGiven that a solution of acetic acid will be acetic, what assumption can be made?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,74,34),(1710,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','With the assumption of an acidic solution, the C.B. equation simplifies as shown.\n\nGiven that acetic acid is a weak acid, and that its initial concentration is larger than its Ka value, what further assumption can be made in the M.B. equation?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,75,35),(1711,'Systematic Equations: Assumptions','With these two assumptions, the system of equations is simplified as shown. The mathematical solution is more readily obtained than it is without the assumptions.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,76,36),(1712,'pH of 0.10 M Acetic Acid','The calculated pH without approximations is  2.87.\n\nThe calculated pH with approximations is 2.87. (The difference is in non-significant digits.)\n\nThe error introduced by the approximation is generally considered acceptable if less than 5%. In this case, the error would be < 1%.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,78,37),(1713,'Mixture of Acetic Acid and Hydrochloric Acid','The systematic equations approach will now be applied to a mixture of 0.10 M acetic acid and 0.010 M hydrochloric acid. \n\nAssumptions will then be made if possible.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,79,38),(1714,'Incorrect','When dissolving only acid, it can be assumed that the final solution will be acidic. In this case, the concentration of hydroxide will typically be negligible.\n\nThe converse applies when dissolving only base (i.e., hydronium negligible).\n\nExceptions may occur in very dilute solutions of acid/base.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,39),(1715,'Correct','Note that two of the assumptions were mathematically equivalent, and can be rationalized chemically.\n\n[OH-] << [H3O+]\n\nThis assumption is valid since it will be acidic solution.\n\n[OH-] << [CH3COO–]\n\nThis assumption is valid since acetic acid produces an acetate for every hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,74,40),(1716,'Incorrect','In most cases, the equilibrium dissociation for a weak acid will favor the acid species rather than the conjugate base. \n\n(The possible exception is when very dilute.)',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,41),(1717,'Chemical Prediction','What acid do you think will be the principal determinant of [H3O+]?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,61,42),(1718,'Incorrect','Although the hydrochloric acid is more dilute, it is a strong acid and acetic acid is a weak acid. The concentration difference is unlikely to be sufficient to overcome the difference in acid strength. \n\nRecall: The pH of 0.010 M HCl was 2.00 and the pH of 0.10 M CH3COOH was 2.87.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,43),(1719,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The HCl is likely to be the main determinant of the pH of the system. \n\nHow many equations should be written to calculate the pH using the systematic approach? (Not including the omnipresent ionization of water.)',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,81,44),(1720,'Incorrect','Water is a very weak acid. It may contribute to the observed pH in very dilute solutions of acid or base, but normally will exert little if any effect when an strong/weak acid or base is present.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,45),(1721,'Incorrect','Since HCl is a strong acid, it does not have an associated equilibrium equation. There is only the equilibrium equation for acetic acid.\n\nThe charge balance equation ensures the net charge of the solution is zero. Since there is only one solution, there is only one charge balance equation.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,46),(1722,'Incorrect','Since HCl is a strong acid, it does not have an associated equilibrium equation. There is only the equilibrium equation for acetic acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,47),(1723,'Incorrect','The charge balance equation ensures the net charge of the solution is zero. Since there is only one solution, there is only one charge balance equation.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,48),(1724,'Incorrect','There are two acids that dissociate (albeit to different degrees). Two mass balance equations are therefore required to keep track of the non-hydronium species.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,49),(1725,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','You have correctly identified the number of equations required to systematically determine the pH of the mixture.\n\nIs the equilibrium equation for the acetic acid in the mixture with hydrochloric acid any different than for acetic acid alone?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,84,50),(1726,'Incorrect','Equilibrium equations are invariant. The presence of additional equilibrium reactions or species does not affect the equilibrium equation for the dissociation of acetic acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,51),(1727,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Which of the equations shown is the correct charge balance equation for a mixture of hydrochloric acid and acetic acid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,82,52),(1728,'Incorrect','Remember that the charge balance equation balances all of the charges in the entire solution. This equation must therefore include ions from both the dissociation of acetic acid and from the dissociation of hydrochloric acid.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,53),(1729,'Incorrect','There is only one concentration of hydronium in a solution regardless of the acid source. There is no need to count its concentration twice just because there are two acids in solution.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,54),(1730,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The charge balance equation for the mixture must include both the chloride and acetate counter-ions, plus the usual hydronium and hydroxide.\n\nAre the two mass balance equations for the mixture any different than the mass balance equations for hydrochloric acid and acetic acid separately?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,86,55),(1731,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. The equilibrium expression for the dissociation of acetic acid is unchanged.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,85,56),(1732,'Incorrect','Hydronium notwithstanding, the hydrochloric acid and acetic acid to produce the same ions in solution. The mass balance equations are therefore unchanged.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,57),(1733,'Systematic Equations for the Mixture','Correct. We now have a complete set of equations for the mixture of 0.10 M acetic acid and 0.010 M hydrochloric acid.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,87,58),(1734,'Sytematic Equations: Assumptions','What assumptions can make to simplify the solution to this system of equations?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,87,59),(1735,'A Potentially Good Assumption','If you assume that [CH3COO-] << [Cl-], then you have assumed that the acetic acid does not contribute to the pH of the solution of 0.010 M hydrochloric acid and 0.10 M acetic acid.\n\nThis may or may not be the case. For the moment, let\'s assume its not a valid assumption and continue.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,66,60),(1736,'Simplified System of Equations','With the assumptions that [OH-] and the dissociation of acetic acid are negligible, the equations simplify as shown above. \n\nThe equations can be algebraically reduced to a quadratic equation in terms of hydronium.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,89,61),(1737,'Solving the Simplified Equation','The calculated pH is 1.99. If we had assumed the acetic acid had no effect on the pH with hydrochloric acid present, the calculated pH would have been 2.00. Thus, such as assumption would have been acceptable.\n\nWhen would this assumption become less likely to be valid?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,90,62),(1738,'Incorrect','Both the concentration of hydrochloric acid relative to the acetic acid and the strength of the weak acid will affect the contribution of the weak acid to the overall solution pH.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,63),(1739,'Correct. Both the concentration of strong acid and strength of the weak acid are important.','With 0.0010 M HCl (aq) and 0.10 M CH3OOH (aq), the pH would 2.71 (vs. 3.00 for HCl alone). \n\nWith Ka = 1.8E-3 for 0.10 M weak acid (vs. 1.8E-5 for acetic acid) the pH with 0.010 M HCl (aq) would be 1.71 (vs. 1.99 in the current acetic acid mixture).',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,66,64),(1740,'Success!','Congratulations! You have complete this scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,55,65),(1741,'Incorrect','If 0.10 M acetic acid had minimal effect on the pH when mixed with 0.010 M hydrochloric acid, then a weak acid with a smaller dissociation constant will have even less effect (i.e., virtually none).',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:29:56','2016-05-31 01:29:56',54,54,66),(1742,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','Iron is the second most abundant metal in the Earth’s crust, the main component of many structural materials (e.g., various types of steel), and an important dietary element with important biochemical roles.',1,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,18,1),(1743,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of iron in a sample can be determined spectrophotometrically. Phenanthroline is a ligand that can coordinate to iron(II) as shown above. The iron(ii) phenanthroline complex has an orange colour, whereas the iron(II) and phenanthroline alone have no colour.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,19,2),(1744,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of iron originally present in a solution is proportional to the amount of the orange complex formed. The amount of complex formed can be measured from the amount of green light that is absorbed by the solution. The details of this type of measurement are explained in another unit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,19,3),(1745,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','For this exercise, it is sufficient to know that the solution containing iron and phenanthroline is aliquoted into a transparent sample cell, light with a wavelength of 554 nm passes through the sample cell, and the amount of light lost traversing the cell is measured.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,22,4),(1746,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The amount of light lost traversing the sample is used to calculate its “absorbance.”  To ensure that the light lost is attributable to the absorption of photons by the iron(II) phenanthroline complex, the absorbance of the sample cell containing only solvent is measured as a negative control.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,23,5),(1747,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','The difference between the absorbance, A, measured for the sample and the blank is linearly proportional to the concentration, c, of the iron(II) phenanthroline complex, although deviations from linearity can sometimes be observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,24,6),(1748,'Background: Spectrophotometric Determination of Iron','This is an example of a calibration curve that plots absorbance, A, versus the concentration, c, of an analyte. The slope, k, of the line of best fit through the data points can be used in combination with the equation A = kc to determine the concentration of iron in an unknown solution.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,26,7),(1749,'Scenario','You will statistically analyze calibration data for the analysis of iron using phenanthroline and spectrophotometry. The calibration data will be used to determine the concentration of iron(II) in an unknown sample, and your results will be compared to the results from another analysis.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,28,8),(1750,'Raw Data','The table shows the raw data measured for the blank and four replicates each of six standard solutions with different concentrations of iron(II) in the presence of excess phenanthroline. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,37,9),(1751,'Blank Corrected Data','The table now shows the data for the four replicates of each standard solution with the average value of the blank samples subtracted. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,38,10),(1752,'Do Not Ignore Blank Samples!','Blank samples, a type of negative control, are very important. Measurement of blank samples allows data to be corrected for contributions to a measured signal that do not arise from the analyte.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,11),(1753,'F-test?','An F-test is used to compare the precision between two measurements. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,NULL,12),(1754,'G-test?','A G-test is used identify outliers, assuming a normally distributed data set. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,NULL,13),(1755,'t-test?','A t-test is typically used to determine if two data sets are significantly different from one another. \n\nWill this statistical test be useful at this point in processing the data as a calibration plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,NULL,14),(1756,'Plot of the Data','The graph shows the data for each replicate of the standard solutions. \n\nAre you satisfied with this plot?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,36,15),(1757,'Averages and Standard Deviations','The table now shows the average absorbance values and their standard deviations for the six standard solutions.\n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,39,16),(1758,'Calibration Plot','The graph shows the average measured absorbance versus the concentration of iron(II). The error bars represent one standard deviation. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,35,17),(1759,'Be Critical of the Data!','Fitting the data with a line would often be logical at this point. However, the error bars are significantly larger for two of the standard solutions than for the others. \n\nYou would be well-advised to re-examine the data table--the larger errors do not appear to be due to greater random error.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,18),(1760,'Consider a Different Option','The t-test is not useful at this point in the data analysis because there is no second data set to which to compare the current data set.\n\nSimilarly, the F-test is not useful without a second data for comparison.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,19),(1761,'G-Test Results','For each standard concentration, the table shows the calculated G-value for the data point furthest from the mean of all of the replicate values. The critical G-value is 1.463 (at 95% confidence).\n\nWhat data points can be rejected from the data set as outliers?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,40,20),(1762,'Incorrect','If the calculated G-value for a data point is larger than the critical G-value for the desired confidence level, then that point can be rejected as an outlier.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,21),(1763,'Mind Your Data!','When possible, replicate data points are plotted on graphs as an average value with error bars representing the standard deviation.\n\nIn addition, do one or more points appear to be anomalous?',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,22),(1764,'Revised Data Set','The revised data set, with outliers removed, is shown. The averages and standard deviations have been recalculated.\n\nNow how do you want to proceed with the analysis?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,41,23),(1765,'Calibration Plot (Outliers Removed)','The graph shows the average measured absorbance versus the concentration of iron(II). The error bars represent one standard deviation. \n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,42,24),(1766,'Fitted Calibration Plot','The entire range of data has been fitted with a line using least-squares regression. \n\nAre you satisfied with this plot?\n\nRecall: A plot of absorbance versus concentration is expected to be linear, with the general form A = kc, although deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,43,25),(1767,'Recall: Backgound Information','A plot of absorbance versus concentration is expected to be linear, with the general form A = kc, although deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,42,26),(1768,'Partial Linear Fit to Calibration Plot','What range of standard solutions do you want to fit with a line?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,42,27),(1769,'Good Thinking but not the Best Choice','There are many instances in which non-linear fits are warranted, and other instances where a purely empirical fit to data is useful. In this case, however, a linear trend is expected from first principles and is best to work within these constraints.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,28),(1770,'Not a Good Fit','The data point for the standard solution with the highest concentration clearly deviates from the linear trend. It was also noted that deviations from linearity are sometimes observed for A > 1. This point should be excluded from the linear fit.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,29),(1771,'Two Points Do Not Make a Line','At least three points are needed to fit a straight line (and preferably more in practice).',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,30),(1772,'Calibration Result','A line through all of the data points except the highest concentration of standard solution is shown with its equation of fit.\n\nAlso shown are the absorbance values and calculated concentrations for four replicate measurements of an unknown iron(II)-containing solution.\n\nHow do you want to proceed?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,48,31),(1773,'Not a Bad Choice, Not the Best Choice','Although three or four data points could define a straight line, it is clear from extrapolating the corresponding linear fits that all the data up to and including the fifth point fall on a line.\n\nIn general, it is best to fit as many points as possible without reducing the quality of the fit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,44,32),(1774,'Save Yourself Some Work','While statistical tests are important tools for making decision, your critical thinking skills remain essential.\n\nFrom inspection, there is clearly no outlier in this data set.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,33),(1775,'Uknown Sample Results','The summary of results for your analysis of the unknown sample is shown.\n\nHow will you report your overall result with 95% confidence?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,49,34),(1776,'Incorrect','Neither the G-statistic nor the F-statistic will help you report a confidence interval.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,54,35),(1777,'t-Test Result','The calculated value of t was less than the critical value at the 95% confidence level. \n\nWhat do you conclude?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,52,36),(1778,'Additional Comparison','How will you determine if there is a significant difference in average result between the two analyses?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:27','2016-05-31 01:30:27',55,51,37),(1779,'Review Hypothesis Testing','Many statistical tests evaluate the null hypothesis 