),(1787,'Introduction','This scenario will ask you to work through a set of question that originally appeared on the CHEM 211 2015 midterm exam.  \n\nIn order to help you prepare for your next test/exam, you will be asked to explain your decision at several points.  \n\nTo proceed with the scenario, click BEGIN.',1,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,1),(1788,'UV-vis spectra of an acid/base indicator','Bromocresol green is a pH indicator dye with pKa = 4.8. Its absorption spectra in 1.0 M HCl (aq) (dashed line) and in 1.0 M NaOH (aq) (solid line) are shown in the graph below. \n\nBased on the information given, which line (I or II) corresponds to the acidic form of bromocresol green?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,91,2),(1789,'Are you sure?','Recall that the dashed line (I) is for BCG in 1.0 M HCl (aq) and the solid line (II) is for BCG in 1.0 M NaOH (aq).\n\nWhich of these will contain the acidic form of BCG?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,91,3),(1790,'Absorbance spectra and colour','Ok, we\'ve established that the dashed line (I) corresponds to the acidic form of BCG.\n\nBased on the wavelength of maximum absorption, what colour will bromocresol green appear in the HCl (aq) solution?',0,0,0,1,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,91,4),(1791,'Incorrect','You should review the concepts of acids and bases before trying this scenario again.',0,0,1,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,5),(1792,'Uh oh...','That\'s not quite right.  Recall that the colour that a solution appears is not the same as the colour that it absorbs.  \n\nLet\'s take a step back before trying again.  \n\nWhat colour of light will be **ABSORBED** by bromocresol green in its acidic form (I, dashed line)?',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,91,6),(1793,'Jablonski energy level diagrams','Draw and label Jablonski diagrams illustrating the origin of the two absorption bands indicated i