owing is an advantage of a spectrophotometer with a single-beam photodiode array (PDA) detector compared to a double-beam spectrophotometer with two PMT detectors?',0,0,0,1,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,22),(1809,'Correct!','Photodiode array detectors collect the entire range of wavelengths dispersed by the grating, with each diode acting as its own exit slit. \n\nAs a result, instruments with a PDA detector:\n(1) allow faster measurements (the whole spectrum can be measured at once)\nAND\n(2) do not require a moving grating',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,23),(1810,'Ooops','That\'s not quite right.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,24),(1811,'Oops','That\'s not quite right',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,25),(1812,'Oops','That\'s not quite right...',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,26),(1813,'That\'s not quite right...','As stated in the problem, the double-beam instrument uses two different PMT detectors, which will each experience their own noise.  It\'s therefore not possible to correct for detector variations with this setup.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,27),(1814,'That\'s not quite right...','Remember that the double-beam instrument uses a grating monochromator with an entrance slit and an exit slit.  The detected wavelength is selected by adjusting the angle of the grating, so that the desired wavelength passes through the exit slit.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,28),(1815,'Incorrect.','PDA instruments are usually single-beam instruments, and thus are unable to correct for noise.',0,0,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,29),(1816,'You\'re done!','Congratulations!  You have completed this scenario.',0,1,0,0,'2016-05-31 01:30:47','2016-05-31 01:30:47',56,NULL,30),(1817,'Equilibrium','The following scenario is based on question 4 from this year\'s C